# Git Commit Conventions

## Semantic Commit Messages (Conventional Commits)

Use semantic commit message format for all commits:

### Format

```
<type>(<scope>): <subject>

<body>

<footer>
```

### Types

- `feat`: New feature
- `fix`: Bug fix
- `docs`: Documentation changes
- `style`: Code style changes (formatting, semicolons, etc.)
- `refactor`: Code refactoring (no feature change or bug fix)
- `perf`: Performance improvements
- `test`: Adding or updating tests
- `build`: Build system or dependency changes
- `ci`: CI/CD changes
- `chore`: Other changes (maintenance, tooling, etc.)

### Examples

**Good:**
```bash
git commit -m "feat: add dark mode toggle"
git commit -m "fix: resolve weight input validation issue"
git commit -m "refactor: improve IndexedDB error handling"
git commit -m "docs: update README with deployment instructions"
git commit -m "style: format code with prettier"
git commit -m "build: configure GitHub Pages deployment"
```

**Bad:**
```bash
git commit -m "Fixed bug"
git commit -m "Update stuff"
git commit -m "Changes"
```

### Scope (Optional)

Scope indicates what part of the codebase is affected:

```bash
git commit -m "feat(ui): add theme toggle button"
git commit -m "fix(db): handle IndexedDB connection errors"
git commit -m "refactor(components): extract ExerciseCard logic"
```

### Body and Footer (Optional)

For complex changes, add a body:

```bash
git commit -m "feat: add session completion tracking

- Store session entries in component state
- Save all entries on Complete Session click
- Add error handling for failed saves"
```

## Do NOT Include Co-authored-by Trailers

Never add `Co-authored-by` trailers to commit messages, especially from AI agents or automated tools.

**Bad:**
```bash
git commit -m "fix: resolve bug" --trailer "Co-authored-by: Cursor <cursoragent@cursor.com>"
```

**Good:**
```bash
git commit -m "fix: resolve bug"
```

### When Running Git Commands

When executing git commit commands:
- Use semantic commit message format
- Do not add `--trailer` flags
- Do not include `Co-authored-by` lines
- Keep commits clean and professional
